Task 1 — Import Bastion Host EC2 Instance

Part A — Import with Hardcoded AMI

Step 1 — Write the import block

Create or update imports.tf with the following:
# imports.tf

import {
  to = aws_instance.web
  id = "i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c"
}

Step 2 — Run terraform plan (first time)
terraform plan
Since no resource block exists yet for aws_instance.web, Terraform will prompt you to auto-generate the configuration:


╷
│ Error: Configuration for import target does not exist
│
│ The configuration for the given import target aws_instance.web does not
│ exist. If you wish to automatically generate the configuration for this
│ resource, use the -generate-config-out option.
╵

Step 3 — Generate the configuration
Run the following command to auto-generate the resource block into a new file:
terraform plan -generate-config-out=generated.tf
This creates a generated.tf file with all attributes pulled from the real EC2 instance in AWS.

Step 4 — Fix conflicting attributes in generated.tf
Open generated.tf. The auto-generated file will contain conflicting arguments that must be commented out or removed. Based on the errors you will encounter:

│ Error: Conflicting configuration arguments
│ "ipv6_address_count": conflicts with ipv6_addresses
│ "private_dns_name_options": conflicts with ...
│ "cpu_core_count": conflicts with cpu_threads_per_core
Comment out the conflicting fields. The most common ones to remove/comment are:


# Comment out these conflicting attributes in generated.tf:
# ipv6_address_count      = 0       ← conflicts with ipv6_addresses
# private_dns_name_options = {}     ← conflicts with hostname_type
💡 Tip: Keep removing/commenting any attribute that Terraform flags as conflicting and re-run terraform plan until no errors remain.

Step 5 — Run terraform plan again
terraform plan

Expected output:
aws_instance.web: Preparing import... [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]
aws_instance.web: Refreshing state... [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]

Plan: 1 to import, 0 to add, 0 to change, 0 to destroy.

Step 6 — Run terraform apply
terraform apply -auto-approve

Expected output:
aws_instance.web: Importing... [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]
aws_instance.web: Import complete [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]

Apply complete! Resources: 1 imported, 0 added, 0 changed, 0 destroyed.


