Part B — Refactor to Dynamic AMI
Step 7 — Create the data source

Create data.tf with the following:


# data.tf
data "aws_ami" "example" {
  name_regex       = "ubuntu/images/hvm-ssd-gp3/ubuntu-noble-24.04-amd64-server-20260313"
  owners           = ["099720109477"]
}

Pickup the name_tegex from ec2 UI console and the owner ID in AMI EC2 Console.


Step 8 — Update the AMI reference in generated.tf
Find the ami line in generated.tf and replace the hardcoded value with the data source reference:

# generated.tf — Before
ami = "ami-05d2d839d4f73aafb"   # hardcoded

# generated.tf — After
ami = data.aws_ami.example.id   # dynamic

Step 9 — Run terraform plan
terraform plan

Expected output:
data.aws_ami.example: Reading...
data.aws_ami.example: Read complete after 1s [id=ami-05d2d839d4f73aafb]
aws_instance.web: Refreshing state... [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]

No changes. Your infrastructure matches the configuration.
