Task 3 — Lifecycle Rule on Auto Scaling Group
Step 1 — Update desired_capacity and add lifecycle block
In generated2.tf, update the aws_autoscaling_group.example resource:

resource "aws_autoscaling_group" "example" {
  name             = "testASG"
  desired_capacity = 2       # ← Changed from 1 to 2
  min_size         = 1
  max_size         = 1

  vpc_zone_identifier = ["subnet-xxxxxxxx"]

  launch_template {
    id      = aws_launch_template.example.id
    version = "$Default"
  }

  # ✅ Lifecycle block — prevents Terraform from enforcing desired_capacity
  lifecycle {
    ignore_changes = [desired_capacity]
  }
}

Step 2 — Run terraform plan
terraform plan
Expected output:

data.aws_ami.example: Reading...
data.aws_ami.example: Read complete after 1s [id=ami-05d2d839d4f73aafb]
aws_instance.web: Refreshing state... [id=i-07e9ebbaaa6dad13c]
aws_launch_template.example: Refreshing state... [id=lt-0f5566dcbc56782b9]
aws_autoscaling_group.example: Refreshing state... [id=testASG]

No changes. Your infrastructure matches the configuration.
💡 Even though desired_capacity = 2 in code but 1 is running in AWS, Terraform shows No changes because of ignore_changes = [desired_capacity].

Step 3 — Run terraform apply
terraform apply -auto-approve
Expected output:
Apply complete! Resources: 0 added, 0 changed, 0 destroyed.
✅ Task 3 Complete


